WEBVTT

02:02.456 --> 02:03.958
Are you gonna paint,
or are you just gonna

02:03.958 --> 02:05.876
sit there staring
at the sky all day?

02:06.585 --> 02:08.337
I'm waitin'
on the right conditions.

02:10.840 --> 02:13.509
Only a depressive
loser like you

02:13.509 --> 02:15.427
would stare at a blue sky
and hope for clouds.

02:15.427 --> 02:16.929
It's a study
of the light.

02:17.221 --> 02:18.889
Clouds are more interestin'.

02:19.515 --> 02:20.724
Well, can you come help me

02:20.724 --> 02:22.184
with the garden
while you wait?

02:22.184 --> 02:23.352
Yeah,
I'm not eatin' anything

02:23.352 --> 02:24.562
that comes outta there.

02:25.020 --> 02:26.021
Why not?

02:26.272 --> 02:27.648
Just 'cause you read
about plants

02:27.648 --> 02:29.233
on the internet for an hour

02:29.233 --> 02:30.860
does not make you
an actual gardener.

02:31.318 --> 02:33.654
Your basil from last week
tasted like chlorine.

02:33.654 --> 02:35.865
Oh, so you'd rather eat food
that comes out

02:35.865 --> 02:37.825
of a meat printer
in orbit somewhere?

02:37.825 --> 02:39.243
Yeah. Lesser of two evils.

02:42.538 --> 02:43.914
Okay, there's somethin'.

02:47.960 --> 02:51.005
Also, Mom looked upset.

02:51.005 --> 02:53.924
Did something happen while
you guys were out job hunting?

02:54.633 --> 02:55.843
She's just tired.

02:59.847 --> 03:01.140
Did she find anything?

03:01.140 --> 03:02.474
She will.

03:03.017 --> 03:04.268
Now, plant your vegetables.
I'm tryin' to focus.

03:17.197 --> 03:18.324
You're kiddin' me.

03:21.285 --> 03:22.953
Thought this one
was headin' east.

03:23.495 --> 03:25.539
Yeah, I think
it's a different one.

03:26.874 --> 03:28.626
Hey,
park somewhere else!

03:29.877 --> 03:31.378
People live down here!

03:50.189 --> 03:51.398
<i>Some of you may not be</i>

03:51.398 --> 03:52.858
<i>old enough to remember it,</i>

03:53.484 --> 03:56.278
<i>but life before First Contact
was extremely difficult.</i>

03:56.278 --> 03:58.572
<i>Nearly every human
had to waste</i>

03:58.572 --> 04:00.532
<i>most of their lives working,</i>

04:00.532 --> 04:02.326
<i>and without our technology,</i>

04:02.326 --> 04:04.119
<i>you could only produce
basic commodities</i>

04:04.119 --> 04:06.747
<i>by slowly destroying
your own habitat.</i>

04:07.289 --> 04:09.291
<i>Now, maybe we should have
intervened earlier,</i>

04:09.291 --> 04:11.710
<i>but our scouting fleet
had been watching you</i>

04:11.710 --> 04:13.837
<i>since the year you call 1953.</i>

04:13.837 --> 04:16.340
<i>And if we'd learned anything
about your species,</i>

04:16.340 --> 04:18.092
<i>it's that you weren't
always so quick</i>

04:18.092 --> 04:19.969
<i>to embrace outsiders.</i>

04:19.969 --> 04:21.720
<i>But when we finally landed
our ships</i>

04:21.720 --> 04:23.305
<i>and introduced ourselves</i>

04:23.305 --> 04:24.807
<i>five years ago today,</i>

04:25.391 --> 04:27.309
<i>well, sure, a few of you
thought we were funny-looking,</i>

04:27.309 --> 04:28.936
<i>and some of your governments</i>

04:28.936 --> 04:30.229
<i>did their best
to keep us out...</i>

04:31.689 --> 04:33.649
<i>...but your most
forward-thinking</i>

04:33.649 --> 04:35.567
<i>business leaders saw
the opportunities we brought</i>

04:35.567 --> 04:38.904
<i>for wealth-creation
and industrial efficiency.</i>

04:40.990 --> 04:43.325
<i>- And humankind</i>

04:43.325 --> 04:45.202
<i>finally joined
the rest of the universe</i>

04:45.202 --> 04:47.246
<i>in a new era of prosperity.</i>

04:47.955 --> 04:49.581
<i>That's it for today's lesson.</i>

04:49.581 --> 04:50.958
<i>Once again, my name is...</i>

04:53.168 --> 04:55.170
<i>And I look forward to getting
to know all of you better.</i>

04:55.170 --> 04:56.922
<i>You may now remove your nodes.</i>

05:03.387 --> 05:04.555
So, yeah.

05:07.057 --> 05:08.475
There's your new curriculum.

05:09.685 --> 05:12.271
No more English Lit.

05:12.271 --> 05:13.772
From now on,
you'll be learning

05:13.772 --> 05:16.358
Vuvv Culture and History.

05:18.694 --> 05:21.280
And yes, that, um, thing,

05:21.947 --> 05:23.657
it's gonna be
your new teacher now.

05:23.657 --> 05:25.617
- Save it, please.

05:26.785 --> 05:29.038
Apparently,
my microscopic salary

05:29.038 --> 05:31.165
is too much of a burden
on the school.

05:32.291 --> 05:34.209
I have been underbid

05:34.209 --> 05:36.837
by the little boxes
on your foreheads.

05:39.923 --> 05:41.884
So congratulations, folks.

05:43.469 --> 05:44.887
You're finally rid of me.

05:59.735 --> 06:01.904
<i>...please come to the office.</i>

06:23.550 --> 06:25.803
You know, you really captured
his essence.

06:36.063 --> 06:37.564
I'm thinkin' maybe...
maybe his face

06:37.564 --> 06:39.358
could use a little
more detail, though.

06:46.824 --> 06:47.950
See?

06:47.950 --> 06:49.034
The resemblance.

06:49.952 --> 06:51.120
It's like a photograph.

06:51.120 --> 06:52.746
Exactly.

06:57.042 --> 06:58.168
You're new here?

06:59.086 --> 07:00.254
Just started today.

07:01.213 --> 07:02.297
Yeah, I noticed.

07:04.341 --> 07:06.802
You're in my home room.
Mr. Stanley's.

07:07.469 --> 07:09.638
The hologram formerly known
as Mr. Stanley.

07:14.685 --> 07:15.936
I'm Adam.

07:17.563 --> 07:18.647
Chloe.

07:25.487 --> 07:28.157
We had a perfectly decent
house in the suburbs,

07:28.157 --> 07:30.951
until the Vuvv built a Gorging
Complex right above it.

07:30.951 --> 07:32.494
- That sucks.
- Yeah.

07:33.453 --> 07:35.205
They bought out
all the lots around us.

07:35.205 --> 07:37.124
My dad was the last holdout.

07:37.124 --> 07:39.543
But the debris got so bad,
that when he finally sold,

07:39.543 --> 07:41.545
it barely paid us enough
for the gas money to get here.

07:41.545 --> 07:42.629
Jesus.

07:43.046 --> 07:44.631
Wait, so why here?

07:44.631 --> 07:45.924
You guys got family in town
or somethin'?

07:45.924 --> 07:47.384
Yeah.

07:47.384 --> 07:48.969
We were at my uncle's
for a bit.

07:48.969 --> 07:50.345
Technically, we still are
if anyone asks,

07:50.345 --> 07:51.763
since it's in the district

07:52.055 --> 07:53.765
and that's why I'm allowed
to come here.

07:53.765 --> 07:55.350
Wait, why "technically"?

07:55.350 --> 07:57.311
Well, their house
flooded last week,

07:57.686 --> 07:58.979
so we had to move out.

07:58.979 --> 08:00.397
Damn, I'm... I'm sorry.

08:00.898 --> 08:01.940
Where are you now?

08:02.524 --> 08:03.817
You know, we're moving around.

08:03.817 --> 08:05.694
A motel,
when we can afford it.

08:05.694 --> 08:07.196
And when you can't?

08:23.712 --> 08:24.963
Was he a good teacher?

08:26.381 --> 08:27.507
Yeah, I guess.

08:29.051 --> 08:30.928
Always seemed like
he hated his job,

08:32.179 --> 08:33.639
but must have meant
a lot to him.

08:36.016 --> 08:37.809
This sort of thing's getting
way too common.

08:38.268 --> 08:39.269
I know.

08:46.443 --> 08:47.444
Hey.

08:48.195 --> 08:49.696
You guys got a place
to stay tonight?

08:51.198 --> 08:52.574
We'll figure something out.

08:56.536 --> 08:58.163
I got kind of a crazy idea.

09:22.938 --> 09:24.398
We really just can't tell you

09:24.398 --> 09:26.191
how grateful we are,
Mrs. Campbell.

09:26.525 --> 09:27.609
Truly.

09:27.609 --> 09:29.111
Well, happy to help.

09:30.195 --> 09:33.907
Adam is a very empathetic kid.

09:33.907 --> 09:35.409
Not a kid, Mom.

09:35.409 --> 09:36.618
And just so you know,

09:36.618 --> 09:38.829
we're not the type of family
that typically lives out of our car.

09:38.829 --> 09:40.038
Dad.

09:40.914 --> 09:43.542
We actually had a pretty nice
nest egg for a while there.

09:44.918 --> 09:47.879
If I'd just put it all into
Vuvv tech, whoo,

09:47.879 --> 09:50.048
- we'd be great right now.

09:50.549 --> 09:53.010
Well, none of us
were prepared.

09:53.802 --> 09:56.138
Now, we just have to adapt.

09:56.972 --> 09:58.140
That's right.

09:58.890 --> 10:01.018
- You hear that, Hunter?
- Yeah, I heard her.

10:02.394 --> 10:04.896
Anyway, um,
it's so nice to finally

10:04.896 --> 10:07.482
be sitting at a real table
and eating some real food.

10:07.482 --> 10:08.900
It's not real food.

10:08.900 --> 10:10.277
Hunter.
- It's not.

10:10.652 --> 10:12.029
I see how they make it.

10:12.446 --> 10:14.656
They just paste synthetic
cow cells into a mold.

10:15.490 --> 10:16.616
And they print it.

10:17.743 --> 10:18.952
- By the yard.
Hey.

10:18.952 --> 10:20.037
By the mile.

10:20.037 --> 10:21.121
Hey!

10:22.581 --> 10:24.708
However you've prepared it,
it's delicious.

10:30.047 --> 10:31.214
So how long are you staying?

10:31.214 --> 10:32.591
Nat! That's rude.

10:32.591 --> 10:34.009
How is that rude?

10:34.676 --> 10:36.678
I told Chloe her family could
stay as long as they needed.

10:36.678 --> 10:38.680
Oh! Okay.

10:39.639 --> 10:41.558
It's not like we're usin' the
basement for anything else.

10:41.558 --> 10:43.352
Mrs. Campbell,

10:43.352 --> 10:46.063
as soon as we can afford it,
we'll start paying rent.

10:47.272 --> 10:48.273
Mm.

10:49.691 --> 10:52.152
You said they were
only stayin' for one night.

10:52.611 --> 10:54.613
Mom,
they were literally sleeping

10:54.613 --> 10:56.239
in a car under an overpass.

10:56.239 --> 10:57.699
There are lots
of people sleepin'

10:57.699 --> 10:59.743
under overpasses, Adam.

11:00.369 --> 11:02.329
They all can't sleep
in our basement.

11:02.329 --> 11:03.413
Why not?

11:04.706 --> 11:06.541
Seriously, why not
if we have the space?

11:06.541 --> 11:09.252
You can go down
to the overpass right now

11:09.252 --> 11:12.089
and find 10 families that need
more help than they do.

11:12.089 --> 11:15.884
Okay, sure, but none of them
have a kid in my class.

11:19.721 --> 11:21.223
Thank you, Chloe.

11:21.723 --> 11:24.643
Of course. Thank you so much
for dinner. It was delicious.

11:24.643 --> 11:25.727
You're welcome.

11:28.230 --> 11:30.857
That was a weird dinner.

11:30.857 --> 11:31.942
Yeah.

11:33.151 --> 11:34.361
Sorry.

11:34.361 --> 11:35.612
It's not your fault.

11:37.739 --> 11:39.241
Hey, what are you doing
this weekend?

11:40.325 --> 11:42.452
Uh, no plans. Why?

11:44.621 --> 11:46.289
You wanna come
scavenging with me?

11:52.379 --> 11:54.589
The trick is finding
which area they use

11:54.589 --> 11:55.882
as a dumping-ground.

11:57.426 --> 11:59.136
Usually,
it's a field like this.

12:01.763 --> 12:03.140
The shitty part is,

12:03.849 --> 12:05.642
you can only salvage
the stuff that survives,

12:05.642 --> 12:07.185
like, the huge drop.

12:09.229 --> 12:12.065
I mean, that is what
the people up there are like.

12:14.901 --> 12:16.862
They'd rather their shit
be destroyed

12:16.862 --> 12:19.197
than end up
in some pleb's living room.

12:21.199 --> 12:22.742
It sounds like
you've been up there.

12:22.742 --> 12:25.203
Nah. But almost did.

12:25.203 --> 12:26.288
- Once.
- Really?

12:26.788 --> 12:28.123
How?

12:28.123 --> 12:29.791
My dad was
a real estate developer,

12:30.750 --> 12:32.586
and, uh, him and his partner

12:32.586 --> 12:35.130
actually had an offer
to subcontract

12:35.630 --> 12:36.840
for a Vuvv firm...

12:38.133 --> 12:40.510
to, uh, design
the human housing

12:40.510 --> 12:42.637
once they started
lettin' people move up there.

12:42.637 --> 12:43.805
Seriously?

12:43.805 --> 12:44.890
Yeah.

12:45.474 --> 12:46.766
He turned 'em down, though.

12:47.392 --> 12:48.393
Why?

12:49.769 --> 12:50.937
He was a proud guy.

12:52.105 --> 12:53.106
Didn't, uh...

12:53.773 --> 12:55.317
Didn't think the terms
were fair.

12:56.443 --> 12:58.195
I mean, I don't think
he really understood

12:58.195 --> 12:59.613
how quickly the wealth
from down here

12:59.613 --> 13:01.323
would migrate up there,
you know.

13:10.248 --> 13:11.333
Where is he now?

13:11.875 --> 13:12.876
My dad?

13:14.085 --> 13:15.670
Dad is in California.

13:18.882 --> 13:20.217
What are you doing?

13:21.426 --> 13:22.552
I'm just sketching.

13:23.637 --> 13:24.721
Sketching me?

13:26.056 --> 13:27.724
Is that okay?

13:36.066 --> 13:37.234
Yeah, um...

13:38.360 --> 13:40.654
My dad has some thing
for the West Coast.

13:41.530 --> 13:43.240
Once business started
dryin' up around here,

13:43.240 --> 13:44.908
he got convinced
that it was the last place

13:44.908 --> 13:46.701
you could make
a decent livin',

13:47.327 --> 13:48.703
so, thought he'd start fresh,

13:49.287 --> 13:50.455
you know,

13:50.455 --> 13:51.998
start sendin' us back checks.

13:53.124 --> 13:54.334
Did it work?

13:54.876 --> 13:56.127
You'd have to ask him.

13:57.712 --> 14:01.091
To do that, you'd have
to find him first, so...

14:06.721 --> 14:08.974
I'm so sorry, Adam.
I didn't mean to bring up...

14:08.974 --> 14:12.269
No, no.
Uh, it's okay. Um...

14:12.269 --> 14:13.687
Can you, uh...

14:14.729 --> 14:17.524
Can you do that look
you were just doin'?

14:18.567 --> 14:19.985
What?

14:20.277 --> 14:23.113
You were, like...
You were doin' this look,

14:23.113 --> 14:24.531
like, when you were
lookin' up.

14:24.531 --> 14:26.199
Can... Can you do that again?

14:30.537 --> 14:31.621
Like this?

14:32.414 --> 14:33.748
Just like that.

14:41.006 --> 14:43.133
<i>Adam! Adam!</i>

14:45.427 --> 14:46.970
Adam!

14:48.263 --> 14:49.347
Come on.

14:52.559 --> 14:53.643
<i>You ready?</i>

14:54.519 --> 14:55.562
<i>Yes.</i>

14:57.397 --> 14:58.940
Sure you're not
gonna make fun of it?

14:58.940 --> 15:00.358
Yes.

15:00.734 --> 15:01.735
All right.

15:02.527 --> 15:04.988
Here we go.

15:07.324 --> 15:10.076
It's too much build-up now.

15:10.076 --> 15:11.661
Oh, my God, Adam!

15:12.037 --> 15:13.371
Uh, can we do this again?
Like, without the towel...

15:13.371 --> 15:14.956
Just show me!

15:14.956 --> 15:16.499
All right.

15:23.089 --> 15:24.090
Oh, my God!

15:25.425 --> 15:28.845
Is that a good "Oh, my God"
or a bad "Oh, my God"?

15:28.845 --> 15:30.013
Very good.

15:30.013 --> 15:31.348
Very, very good.

15:32.098 --> 15:33.600
It's hilarious but...

15:34.225 --> 15:36.227
And it also really
kinda looks like me.

15:36.227 --> 15:38.938
- You like it? Really?

15:38.938 --> 15:41.399
- I really do.

15:41.399 --> 15:43.276
Well, I want you to have it.
It's yours.

15:43.943 --> 15:45.445
Seriously?

15:45.445 --> 15:47.113
Yeah. I mean, well,
you need somethin'

15:47.113 --> 15:48.782
to put on these walls
down here.

15:51.201 --> 15:53.536
This might be the nicest thing
anyone's ever done for me.

15:53.536 --> 15:54.621
Shut up.

15:55.246 --> 15:56.456
Maybe the second-nicest.

15:57.666 --> 15:59.167
What's the first?

15:59.167 --> 16:01.169
Well, I don't wanna
make you jealous,

16:01.503 --> 16:03.338
but there's this kid
in my class

16:03.338 --> 16:05.298
who let my entire family
stay at his house.

16:05.298 --> 16:06.883
- Oh, really?
- Mm-hmm.

16:06.883 --> 16:08.343
Sounds like a real try hard,
that guy.

16:08.343 --> 16:10.512
Well, he's actually
extremely kind.

16:11.096 --> 16:12.097
And smart.

16:12.931 --> 16:14.933
Okay, well, now I am jealous.

16:20.689 --> 16:21.731
Chloe?

16:21.731 --> 16:23.316
Uh, yeah?

16:23.733 --> 16:24.859
Oh, hey, Adam.

16:25.235 --> 16:26.611
What's up, Mr. Marsh?

16:28.196 --> 16:29.197
Uh, what's up?

16:30.365 --> 16:34.953
Oh, did you, uh,
do something with my Q-tips?

16:35.912 --> 16:36.955
No.

16:37.497 --> 16:38.498
Huh.

16:39.916 --> 16:41.209
I can't find them.

16:43.962 --> 16:45.380
Well, good luck.

16:49.426 --> 16:50.719
An interesting piece.

16:53.471 --> 16:54.472
Thanks.

17:25.253 --> 17:27.797
So, you guys steal this stuff,
or what?

17:28.423 --> 17:29.507
We found it.

17:29.507 --> 17:30.675
You gonna buy?

17:31.885 --> 17:34.554
I wish I could. Um...

17:34.554 --> 17:36.848
I'm real short on cash.
But if you two could help...

17:36.848 --> 17:38.725
This isn't a charity booth.
Okay?

17:38.725 --> 17:40.185
So, either pay up

17:40.185 --> 17:42.103
or make room
for the other customers.

17:44.981 --> 17:46.524
What other customers?

17:51.488 --> 17:52.489
Sorry.

17:52.906 --> 17:54.699
I guess this was a bust.

17:55.742 --> 17:56.868
It's okay.

17:56.868 --> 17:59.788
No, it's not, though.
I really wanna be able
to pay you guys rent.

17:59.788 --> 18:01.498
Don't worry about it.

18:01.498 --> 18:02.665
Or at least our share
of the heating bills.

18:02.665 --> 18:04.167
Chloe, it's fine, really.

18:04.167 --> 18:06.544
I don't think
we even have our share.

18:07.295 --> 18:08.838
It might be a cold winter.

18:10.799 --> 18:13.343
Well, you're very sweet
to help me with this.

18:16.012 --> 18:19.098
Hey, it's, uh, you know,
somethin' to do.

18:23.978 --> 18:25.146
Hey, you know, we could...

18:26.773 --> 18:29.192
we could always consider
doing a Courtship Broadcast.

18:30.902 --> 18:31.903
A what?

18:32.821 --> 18:35.615
You know, where you set
your nodes to broadcast

18:35.615 --> 18:37.283
instead of receive,

18:37.283 --> 18:38.785
and then they watch you
while you go on dates.

18:38.785 --> 18:40.578
They actually, like,
pay to watch

18:40.578 --> 18:42.789
and then they send it
straight to your account.

18:42.789 --> 18:44.374
You've never heard about this?

18:46.292 --> 18:47.335
Okay, well...

18:48.253 --> 18:49.337
You know,
they don't have, like,

18:49.337 --> 18:50.713
"dating" in their culture.

18:50.713 --> 18:52.298
They don't have "love."

18:52.298 --> 18:54.217
They reproduce asexually.
They "bud."

18:54.217 --> 18:56.553
So, they find romantic stuff,

18:56.553 --> 18:58.721
like, super exotic
and interesting.

19:01.724 --> 19:04.811
Well, anyway,
it's just a thought.

19:07.564 --> 19:09.983
You don't think that'd be
kinda awkward, though?

19:10.692 --> 19:12.151
Not really.

19:12.151 --> 19:13.611
I don't find being
with you awkward.

19:13.611 --> 19:15.738
It's kinda the opposite
of awkward.

19:18.575 --> 19:20.034
Yeah, um...

19:20.034 --> 19:21.661
Um, I...

19:21.661 --> 19:24.080
I mean, I feel the same way.

19:24.789 --> 19:26.291
That's why we'd probably make

19:26.291 --> 19:27.834
a good Courtship Broadcast, actually.

19:27.834 --> 19:29.002
Now that we're talking
about it.

19:29.002 --> 19:30.378
Yeah, but...

19:30.378 --> 19:32.380
You don't wanna just

19:32.380 --> 19:34.549
let it develop,
like, naturally?

19:35.633 --> 19:37.510
We can still
